<TEXT>
breast cancer screening programs that personally 
review positive or suspicious mammograms could substantially reduce 
the number of breast cancer deaths if used nationwide federal 
health officials said 
the national centers for disease control said in its weekly 
report thursday that breast cancer deaths would be cut dramatically 
if personal followup examinations like that in an inexpensive 
breast cancer screening program used by the rhode island department 
of health is widely instituted 
rhode island cancer registry administrator john fulton who 
worked with the state health department on the program said in a 
telephone interview that mammograms give patients a two or 
threeyear edge on detecting small tumors before they spread and 
when combined with a personal followup procedure can save many 
lives 
physical examination is a very useful technique and we 
advocate its use but we know in women from the ages of 50 and 
above that mammography can actually detect cancers two to three 
years before a physician can actually feel it in a breast 
examination he said to reduce the death rate from breast 
cancer we have to increase the use of mammography 
the national cancer institute and the american cancer society 
both advocate the use of mammography the study says the test has 
been shown in previous research to reduce deaths from breast 
cancer the leading cause of death from malignancy among women 
we would consider anything that we learned from rhode islands 
experience as having relevance to all other states said cdc 
spokesman robert smith the program is relatively new and were 
still at a stage of evaluating but i think the early results are 
encouraging 
the cdc said a preliminary survey of 852 rhode island women 
about 40 years old showed only 37 percent of those responding had 
gotten a mammogram in the past year 70 percent had gotten a breast 
examination from a physician and 35 percent had done both the 
survey conducted last october showed 92 percent saw a physician 
last year 
the screening program which provides mammographies for 50 a 
staff followup of positive suspicious or inconclusive tests and a 
review by a panel of radiologists could serve as a model for use 
in other states fulton said 
fulton said the rhode island statistics for mammograms and 
physical exams are higher than the national average but are far 
from approaching those set for the year 2000 by national cancer 
institute which advocates the use of mammography and physical 
examination in 80 percent of all women age 50 to 70 by that time 
we believe our program will increase the number of mammograms 
because we have lowered the cost and have received a lot of 
physician support in the community fulton said 
