<DOCNO> AP880617-0106 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a diet high in vitamindeficient white rice 
is a primary cause of a disease that kills otherwise healthy 
southeast asian men in their sleep according to a researcher who 
spent three years studying the ailment 
ronald munger a postdoctoral fellow at the university of 
minnesotas division of epidemiology said thursday his studies 
show that stress is not the leading cause of sudden unexpected 
death syndrome as some experts believe he proposed instead that 
it results mainly from thiamine deficiency 
munger presented his findings to a conference of the society for 
epidemiologic research in vancouver british columbia 
suds is the leading cause of death for southeast asian refugee 
men ages 25 to 44 during their first few years in the united 
states the disease has claimed 117 southeast asian refugees since 
1977 according to the centers for disease control in atlanta 
nearly all died in their sleep 
although researchers know the immediate cause of suds is an 
electrical instability of the heart they dont know what causes 
the instability 
the most common theory is that the deaths are caused mainly by 
stress related to immigration and culture shock other possible 
explanations are heart abnormalities or genetic predisposition 
among southeast asians 
munger said he believes all those factors may play a part in 
suds but he places the main blame on the staple of the southeast 
asian diet white rice which is a poor source of vitamins 
brown or unmilled rice is a good source of vitamins 
particularly thiamine but few southeast asians eat it because its 
not considered socially acceptable eighty percent of the thiamine 
is lost in the milling process that produces white rice thiamine 
also known as vitamin b1 is essential to normal nerve function and 
metabolism of carbohydrates 
for his study munger gathered electrocardiographs from 80 
refugee men in thailand in 1985 and 40 refugee men in minnesota 
over the last two years he found ecg abnormalities occurred among 
culturally and genetically diverse groups including japanese 
filipinos vietnamese cambodians laotians and hmong 
but some researchers doubt mungers theory 
the thing i wonder a bit about his hypothesis is that its so 
different from what is usually seen in thiamine deficiency said 
dr gib parrish a medical epidemiologist and pathologist at the 
cdc 
thiamine deficiency often causes inflammation and degeneration 
of the nerves digestive system and heart those also are symptoms 
of the disease beriberi which is caused by a thiamine deficiency 
however most suds victims appear normal before dying 
munger said hes suggesting that there are undocumented effects 
of thiamine deficiency 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

