<TEXT>
the supreme court resolving what it called 
a peculiar battle between two federal appeals courts told one 
of those courts today to tackle an antitrust dispute over the m16 
the us military standard rifle 
the justices unanimously ruled that the chicagobased 7th us 
circuit court of appeals should rule in the case not the 
washingtonbased us court of appeals for the federal circuit 
the justices also said the washingtonbased court was wrong 
when in the interest of justice it ruled in the case after 
deciding it lacked the proper authority to do so 
charles r christianson owner of an m16 parts company called 
international trade services inc sued colt industries operating 
corp in 1984 he charged colt which dominates the market for m16 
sales with violating federal antitrust law 
the lawsuit filed in federal court in chicago contends that 
colt abused patents it held for the rifle and its various parts to 
monopolize the market illegally 
us district judge robert d morgan ruled for christianson and 
colt appealed to the us court of appeals for the federal circuit 
a washingtonbased court that concentrates on patent disputes 
christianson sought to have the case transferred to the 7th 
circuit court and the federal circuit court agreed with him that 
it lacked the jurisdiction to handle colts appeal 
the 7th circuit court however ruled that the federal circuit 
court was clearly wrong in its jurisdictional decision and sent 
the case back to washington 
confronted with the case a second time the washingtonbased 
appeals court last year said that although it lacked the proper 
jurisdiction it would rule in the case 
it then ruled against christianson 
writing for the high court today justice william j brennan 
said the 7th circuit court was wrong about which court had 
jurisdiction and set aside the federal circuit courts ruling on 
the lawsuits merits 
in a victory for christianson the case now heads back to the 
7th circuit court 
the case is christianson vs colt industries 87499 
