<TEXT>
the supreme court today struck down an ohio 
law that exempted from any deadlines the filing of lawsuits against 
outofstate defendants 
the court by an 81 vote ruled that the law unduly interfered 
with interstate commerce 
the decision upheld lower court rulings that an ohio 
manufacturers breachofcontract lawsuit against an illinois 
corporation properly was dismissed for having been filed too late 
the justices said the ohio law that would have allowed the 
manufacturer to sue even after the normal deadline had passed 
discriminated against outofstate businesses 
bendix autolite corp sued midwesco enterprises inc in 1980 
over a coalfired boiler that was installed in a bendix plant at 
fostoria ohio in 1975 
midwesco sought to have the lawsuit dismissed contending that 
under ohio law suits alleging breach of contract or fraud must be 
filed within four years of the alleged wrongdoing 
the lawyers for bendix relied on another ohio law one saying 
lawsuits against outofstate defendants do not have to comply with 
the usual fouryear deadline 
writing for the high court today justice anthony m kennedy 
said the ohio law forced outofstate businesses to choose 
between exposure to the general jurisdiction of ohio courts or 
forfeiture of the statute of limitations defense remaining 
subject to suit in ohio in perpetuity 
saying the law imposed a significant burden on outofstate 
defendants kennedy added the ohio statute imposes a greater 
burden on outofstate companies than it does on ohio companies 
subjecting the activities of foreign and domestic corporations to 
inconsistent regulations 
chief justice william h rehnquist dissented voting to 
reinstate the ohio law 
the case is bendix autolite vs midwesco enterprises 87367 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

