<DOCNO> AP880617-0153 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the occupational safety and health 
administration on friday tightened its regulations on concrete and 
masonary construction saying its new standards will save the lives 
of 120 workers a year 
the new regulations in the making since 1982 require 
additional bracing of concrete and masonry walls and more thorough 
testing of concrete to assure that it has hardened sufficiently 
before braces are removed or loads are put on it 
the changes were prompted by a 1978 accident in which 51 
construction workers plunged to their deaths when scaffolding 
anchored in uncured concrete collapsed on a power plant cooling 
tower being built at willow island wva 
a similar accident occurred in 1973 when 14 workers were killed 
and 34 were injured because of the premature removal of forms 
supporting the 23rd floor of an apartment building under 
construction in fairfax county va 
however the new osha regulations do not address the 
controversial liftslab construction practice involved in the 
collapse last year of the halfbuilt lambiance plaza apartment 
complex in bridgeport conn which killed 28 workers 
as with the willow island and fairfax county accidents osha 
officials determined that the lambiance plaza collapse would not 
have occurred had the contractors involved been complying with 
existing federal regulations 
officials said friday that new safety requirements for 
liftslab construction a process in which floor and roof 
slabs are cast on the ground and then jacked upward into position 
will not be proposed until later this year 
they said the agency is reopening the issue because of new 
technical information arising out of the investigation of the 
lambiance plaza accident 
the new regulations to take effect in 60 days update 1971 
standards to prohibit premature removal of forms require bracing 
for masonry walls for the first time mandate supports for precast 
panels and establish limited access zones around wall construction 
areas 
in addition they recognize new methods for testing concrete 
and to prevent workers from being impaled require that protective 
coverings be placed over exposed reinforcement bars or that the 
bars be bent over 
the changes also remove ambiguities in the old rules making 
it easier and less expensive for employers to protect their 
employees said john pendergrass assistant labor secretary and 
osha administrator 
in addition to saving 120 lives a year osha officials estimate 
that the new regulations will prevent 7000 onthejob injuries 
annually among the nations 38 million construction workers 
compliance is expected to cost contractors an additional 382 
million a year but officials said savings from less property 
damage construction delays and insurance premiums asa result of 
fewer accidents are expected to total nearly 350 million annually 
osha estimated that about 80 percent of the nearly 250000 
masonry and concrete contractors in the country have fewer than 10 
employees and that the cost to those firms would average only 339 
a year a small price to pay for saving lives and reducing the 
number of injuries pendergrass said 
many of the specific changes in the regulations were recommended 
or endorsed by construction unions 
however jim lapping a safety specialist for the aflcios 
building and construction trades department said there was no 
reason to delay the new regulations on liftslab construction 
the ansi american national standards institute committee has 
made its recommendations and there is plenty of information on the 
record lapping said but this administration has not been 
noted to responding quickly or to our advice we still dont have a 
tunnel standard that was proposed in 1972 
lapping said the building trade unions support legislation 
introduced thursday by sen lowell p weicker jr and rep 
christopher shays both rconn that would criminalize 
construction safety law violations and require a professional 
engineer to oversee all work 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

