<TEXT>
during his tenure as us attorney leon kellner 
saw an indictment against panamas gen manuel antonio noriega and 
drug charges against officials in haiti nicaragua bolivia the 
bahamas turks and caicos suriname and cuba 
i had no inkling i would be at the eye of the hurricane and i 
still have trouble understanding it kellner said before his last 
day in office friday im not doing anything profound i just 
take a case where the evidence leads 
kellner spent three years as an assistant and three years as 
chief prosecutor in the southern district of florida among the 
busiest federal districts in the nation 
kellners office indicted leaders of the colombiabased medellin 
cartel responsible for up to 80 percent of us cocaine imports 
and he successfully prosecuted scores of miami police who ran a 
drugripoff ring 
kellner 42 who usually is very serious and lowkey but flashes 
an occasional ironic smile is proud he aimed for the leaders of 
drug rings but says only drying up the demand can really stem 
trafficking 
when i became us attorney one of the things i wanted do was 
go as high up in the narcotics trafficking business as i could 
said kellner and i think thats what i did 
but not without personal danger 
his most chilling moments came after the extradition of medellin 
cartel leader carlos lehder rivas when swat teams and federal 
agents responding to death threats were sent to guard him and his 
family against possible reprisals from the violent drug ring his 
family fled their coral gables home and for a time had to be 
escorted on routine errands 
what is interesting about that episode is that the 
government was prepared to do anything no matter what the cost to 
ensure the safety of people working on the case says kellner 
whose jewish parents fled nazi germany before world war ii 
he contrasts that with the violence the cartel has wreaked on 
colombia where a justice minister an attorney general and 
hundreds of other law enforcement officials have been gunned down 
that experience made him even more militant on winning 
extradition rights from countries which have been traditional 
havens for traffickers 
the reason extradition is so important in my mind is that 
there is a recognition that foreign countries do not enforce 
their own laws because of the power of the cartel the threats of 
the cartel he says 
the noriega indictment and the subequent political firestorm 
