<TEXT>
a bill that some believe is the first step of 
a 3 billion project to map the human genetic pattern passed the 
senate friday by a vote of 88 to 1 
the legislation called the biotechnology competitiveness act 
does not authorize the start of any laboratory research but 
experts in the biotechnology field said the bill creates a 
framework that would enable the start of a major genetic project in 
about two years 
sen william proxmire dwis cast the single dissenting vote 
the bill has four major provisions these are 
establish a 20member national biotechnology policy board to 
review federal research support efforts and to make recommendations 
on biotechnology issues the first report to the president and to 
congress is due by jan 31 1990 
establish an advisory panel on the human genome that will 
develop a strategy needed for a project to map and sequence the 
human genome or genetic pattern experts say that a crash program 
of research on the genome would take seven to 10 years and cost 
about 3 billion 
establish a 10 million biotechnology information center at the 
national library of medicine 
and finally the bill would reauthorize a biomedical ethics 
board that would analyze the reports of the biotechnology policy 
board and the human genome advisory panel 
provisions in the bill are estimated to cost 104 million in 
fiscal year 1989 which begins in october the cost would rise to 
142 million in 1990 154 million in 1991 and 13 million 
annually for the following two yeasrs 
richard d godown president of the industrial biotechnology 
association said the 88 to 1 vote shows the overwhelming support 
of the united states for the biotechnology industry 
godown said that establishing the boards and panels described in 
the bill are essential for organizing the genome research a 
project that may involve hundreds of laboratories and thousands of 
scientists 
this clears the way for the money to be appropriated later 
he said godown said it may be two years before the project is 
organized but that the organizational structure established by the 
bill is the first step 
godown said that private industry and some federal laboratories 
already are studying the human genome and this work will continue 
while the committees conduct their studies 
the human genome is the genetic pattern contained in the human 
chromosones the pattern which is unique to each individual 
determines fundamental physical characteristics many diseases are 
related to genetic patterns and scientists hope that by 
understanding the genome that these diseases can be treated or 
prevented 
godown said understanding the genome is fundamental to the 
revolution occurring in biotechnology 
mapping the sequence of the human genome will determine the 
degree of success we realize from the biotechnology revolution 
he said by understanding the genetic pattern godown said 
scientists will significantly advance an understanding of how the 
human body works 
the bill was drawn up after studies by scientists at the 
national research council strongly supported a federally funded 
effort to map and sequence the human genome 
one major consideration supporting the genome research is 
international competition 
the department of commerce has estimated that the market for 
biotechnology products which would include pharmaceuticals and 
agricultural products will exceed 40 billion a year by 2000 
france germany and japan already have national biotechnology 
programs which includes human genome research 
</TEXT>
