because the drought threatens to make agricultural commodities 
scarce it already is driving up their prices but higher prices 
in turn are likely to shrink federal incomesupport payments that 
growers receive 
the payments are the difference between market prices and 
higher target prices set by congress and adjusted by the secretary 
of agriculture as the difference narrows the farmers payment 
shrinks meanwhile the drought may leave the grower without a crop 
to sell at the higher market levels 
the problem is even worse for many farmers who have received 
part of their incomesupport payments in advance and now are faced 
with the prospect of having to repay part of them 
harkin said it might be possible to reopen the signup period 
for obtaining federal crop insurance 
