the defense department has agreed to accept 
penalties from the environmental protection agency if it violates 
agreements with epa to clean up superfund toxic waste sites 
epa announced friday 
in such a case the department will seek appropriations to make 
the actual transfer of funds from its pocket to epas 5000 for 
the first week of violation and 10000 for subsequent weeks 
the agreement similar to one reached last month with the energy 
department provides for the administrator of epa to settle any 
disputes between the staffs of epa and the department over whether 
a violation has occurred 
amendments to the superfund law in 1986 required epa and the two 
departments to try to agree on a penalty formula leaving the 
actual funds to be appropriated by congress 
if epa assesses a penalty the installation affected must report 
the facts to congress 
we think this provides greater incentive to comply said 
christopher grundler head of epas federal facilities hazardous 
waste compliance office the colonel commanding a base doesnt 
get to be a general if he has to march up to congress to explain 
whats been going on 
federal facilities such as air bases are frequently among the 
most contaminated waste sites because of years of neglect of such 
problems as the disposal of powerful solvents used to clean 
aircraft engines 
though epa can list such sites on its superfund priority list 
the owning agency is responsible for cleanup and epa may spend 
none of its own funds there 
epa must negotiate cleanup agreements in such instances the 
justice department has claimed that any legislation requiring epa 
to order cleanups would unconstitutionally infringe on the 
presidents powers to direct the executive branch 
