and utilities operated at 829 percent of capacity last month a 
02 percentage point increase over april it was the sixth increase 
in eight months and the highest operating level since march 1980 
when the rate hit 837 percent 
some economists expressed concern that the trend will push 
prices higher as manufacturers have difficulty producing enough to 
meet demand but others say the may report is good news because 
operating rates cooled in the hottest industries and increased in 
sectors with excess capacity 
a separate report thursday by the commerce department showed 
business inventories rose 05 percent in april signaling slower 
economic growth for the second quarter business sales fell 02 
percent in the same month 
economists generally take rising inventories as a sign that 
buying demand is declining and as an indication that manufacturers 
may have to reduce production but the report of higher factory 
utilization rates as well as other recent evidence of economic 
strength suggested no significant slowdown 
financial markets largely ignored the government reports 
thursday focusing instead on the inflationary impact of an 
agricultural drought that could raise food prices later this year 
