<TEXT>
more than most lawsuits the landmark 
cipollone cigarette liability case seemed to rest mainly on how the 
questions were framed than on positions the lawyers argued 
the question asked by the cigarette makers was should a company 
really be forced to pay money because a smoker contracted lung 
cancer when she knew people were saying cigarettes were dangerous 
attorneys for rose cipollone who died in 1984 at 58 after four 
decades of smoking put it another way shouldnt the makers of her 
cigarettes be held responsible for their actions in making a 
potentially dangerous product 
and the 4month trial which ended monday with the first 
liability finding against the industry posed a broader question 
is the courtroom the place to change public policy 
the verdict reached by a jury of six new jersey people seemed to 
answer none of those questions 
the panel cleared liggett group inc lorillard inc and philip 
morris inc of conspiring to misrepresent the dangers of smoking 
but it granted 400000 to antonio cipollone in finding that 
liggett which made the cigarettes mrs cipollone smoked before 
warning labels were put on packs in 1966 violated advertising 
promises that its products were safe 
however it answered none to the jurysheet question of what 
damages mrs cipollone sustained 
the jury also partly found against liggett on a failuretowarn 
claim determining the company should have told consumers of 
smokings risks before 1966 that the omission contributed to mrs 
cipollones smoking and that the smoking contributed to her death 
yet the panel said mrs cipollone was mostly responsible for her 
injuries and thus not entitled to damages 
aside from the industrys exoneration on the fraud conspiracy 
claim company lawyers said they essentially won the case because 
the jury found mrs cipollone responsible for her injuries 
supporting the classic industry argument that smokers make an 
independent intelligent choice to puff on cigarettes 
but cipollones lawyers said the verdict supported the charge 
that smoking causes cancer which the industry denies has been 
proven and that actions by a cigarette maker can be blamed for a 
smokers disease 
industry victory proclamations caused some skepticism in 
antismoking ranks 
to me it seems like the captain of the titanic saying just 
a little ice folks said don davis an austin texas attorney 
whose firm handles cigarette liability cases 
the verdict led both sides to promise an appeal they will have 
until june 29 to file posttrial motions with us district judge 
h lee sarokin with oral arguments expected toward the end of 
july the outcome will shape arguments in appeals courts 
a different court the often cited court of public opinion 
must wrestle meanwhile with the significance of the cipollone 
verdict and all other cases like it 
antismoking advocates see liability cases as a way of reducing 
the number of smokers raising the price of cigarettes through 
mounting industry legal bills and drumming up public opinion 
against cigarettes but others dont see that as the role of the 
courts 
im not a big fan of getting social reform by litigation 
said boris yavitz a columbia university business school professor 
with a chair in business ethics 
a jury rules in favor of a plaintiff or defendant but doesnt 
rule on the issue involved he said 
consensus on rules of a society should be reached first through 
public debate and the actions of elected officials and the courts 
should then enforce compliance with what is decided in yavitz 
view 
but the courts have often been put to good use for important 
causes said john f banzhaf a george washington university law 
professor and antismoking activist 
environmental protection and rights for minorities prisoners 
and women have been won and maintained in courtrooms he said 
the courtroom also removes the advantages of lobbyists and 
influence of a powerful institution 
from the point of view of an activist which i am there are a 
number of forums and you use all of them he said 
cigarette liability trials with an individual victim and 
testimony from bereaved family members have a way of personalizing 
the statistics about smokings casualties in his view 
a momentous verdict like in the cipollone case sparks the 
attention of legislators and an antiindustry verdict will spawn 
more filings spreading the industrys legal resources thin and 
creating more opportunity for errors by industry lawyers banzhaf 
contended 
