united airlines filed a complaint friday with the 
department of transportation charging japan air lines with unfair 
competitive practices for blocking japanese travel agents from 
using uniteds apollo computerized reservations system 
the complaint filed in washington contends that jal has 
engaged in discriminatory and anticompetitive practices which 
restrict uniteds access to japanese markets for its apollo system 
while we regret that we have to take a step as serious as this 
filing we must protect our rights to do business in japan said 
john r zeeman uniteds executive vice president for marketing and 
planning in a statement released friday 
jals denial of access to united and covia in japan is 
inconsistent with the basic principles of reciprocity and is 
detrimental to the commercial relationship between the united 
states and japan he said 
covia is the computer reservations subsidiary of ual corp 
uniteds parent and operates the apollo system 
morris simoncelli jals deputy director for public relations 
said he was aware of the complaint but the airlines lawyers in 
washington had not yet seen it 
we cant comment until we have a chance to look at it said 
simoncelli contacted by telephone at jals new york city office 
uniteds complaint alleges that jal has violated the 
international air transport associations fair competitive 
practices act by refusing to permit japanese travel agents to use 
apollo to write tickets on jal in japan 
at the same time there are no restrictions on jal using its own 
computerized reservation system jalcom to write tickets on united 
in japan said rob doughty a united spokesman 
he said us travel agents were also free to issue tickets on 
jal using the apollo system 
united has been trying for more than two years to obtain the 
rights to have apollo issue tickets on jal in japan but jal has so 
far refused to sign the international ticketwriting agreement 
required by japanese banks for settling payments from one airline 
to another doughty said 
the complaint contends that jals refusal to grant ticketing 
authority to united preserves the japanese carriers domestic 
monopoly for its own reservation system 
doughty said uniteds reservations system was more 
sophisticated and offers more benefits than jals but japanese 
travel agents were reluctant to purchase apollo because they could 
not use it to make bookings on jal 
the complaint did not specify how much united has lost in 
potential revenue from jals practices doughty said 
doughty said united hoped that filing the complaint would lead 
jal to lift its restrictions on issuing tickets 
if jal remained intransigent united would ask that the 
transportation department impose forceful retaliatory action 
against jal by barring it from using any us computer reservations 
system for booking and ticketing 
