considered pivotal since farmers is based in los angeles 
arizona the only other state to rule on the matter approved 
batus application 
ms gillespie rejected to farmers arguments that batus was 
unfit to own an insurance company because it also owns cigarette 
companies she said in a telephone interview from her san francisco 
office 
nor was she swayed by a parade of elected state and municipal 
officials who publicly denounced the takeover because bat has 
business interests in racially segregated south africa 
farmers had suggested that its nonsmoker discounts wouldnt 
continue under batus and that tobacco product liability suits 
could drain batus resources 
we did take a look at those issues but we did not find against 
bat on those issues she said 
aside from the government ownership batus met all the tests for 
eligibility to own a california insurer ms gillespie said 
she declined to speculate on the rationale for the prohibition 
on government ownership of an insurer but said the commission 
staff always interprets the code to mean the 10 percent limit 
applies to aggregate ownership by government entities 
this narrow approach has always been the approach of the staff 
in these cases ms gillespie said 
